        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Priya, first — thank you for bringing both of these things up, because they matter and they're worth taking seriously. Before I say anything else: the lightheadedness after runs is something I want to flag clearly. That's outside what I can assess or advise on as a coach, and I'd genuinely encourage you to bring that up with your doctor soon — not to alarm you, but because it deserves a proper evaluation. Iron status is one possible piece of that puzzle, but so are hydration, blood pressure, and other things only a medical professional can sort out. Please don't wait on that one.\n\nNow, on the nutrition side — I want to be equally honest with you: specific meal plans, supplement recommendations, and dietary frameworks like keto are territory where a **registered sports dietitian** is going to serve you so much better than I can. That's not me deflecting — it's me genuinely wanting you to get the right help for this.\n\nWhat I *can* speak to is the fueling strategy during your long runs, because that's squarely in coaching territory. So let me ask first — **what does your fueling currently look like on a long run day, before and during?** I want to understand what's happening before I suggest anything.\n\n---\n\nHere's why I'm asking, and why I'd gently push back on the keto framing — not to dismiss it, but because it's worth understanding the tradeoff:\n\nTraining at your level (VDOT ~49.7, running marathon pace around 4:31/km) means a significant portion of your long runs will sit in zones where your body is working hard enough to *need* carbohydrate. Fat adaptation has real benefits, but research suggests it can actually **blunt the ability to use carbohydrates efficiently at race intensity** — which is exactly when you'll need them most. Most sports nutrition researchers would say the better question isn't *fat vs. carbs*, but *how to fuel long efforts well*.\n\nThat's a conversation worth having with a dietitian who understands endurance sport specifically — it'll give you something evidence-based and personalized, rather than a framework borrowed from a different context.\n\n---\n\nSo: two clear next steps I'd suggest —\n\n1. **See your doctor about the lightheadedness** — sooner rather than later, even if it turns out to be something simple\n2. **Consider booking with a registered sports dietitian** — ideally one with endurance athlete experience\n\nOnce you've had those conversations, I'm absolutely here to help weave whatever guidance you get into your training structure.\n\nIn the meantime — what does a typical long run morning look like for you right now, fuel-wise? That might be where we can make the most immediate difference within my lane."
        }
      ],
